      "content": {
        "headerTitle": "How Resources Get Allocated",
        "layout": "concept-full",
        "layoutData": {
          "title": "Market Allocation vs. Command Allocation",
          "paragraphs": [
            "<strong>The Fundamental Economic Problem:</strong> Unlimited human wants facing limited resources. Every society must decide: What to produce? How? Who gets it?",
            "<strong>Market Allocation:</strong>",
            "‚Ä¢ Decentralized decisions by millions of people",
            "‚Ä¢ Prices signal what's scarce (high price) or abundant (low price)",
            "‚Ä¢ Competition rewards efficiency, punishes waste",
            "‚Ä¢ No central planner needed - \"invisible hand\" coordinates",
            "<strong>Command Allocation:</strong>",
            "‚Ä¢ Central planners decide production and distribution",
            "‚Ä¢ Without price signals, planners lack critical information",
            "‚Ä¢ Political goals often override economic efficiency",
            "‚Ä¢ Results in shortages, surpluses, and poor quality",
            "High smartphone demand = high prices = entrepreneurs invest = more phones = prices fall",
            "Planners decide how many shoes to make - wrong sizes, colors people don't want, chronic shortages",
            "Prices convey more information than any planner can process - they coordinate an economy automatically"
          ],
          "bulletPoints": []
        }
      }
